 political leaders wielded the promise of national progress to broker consensus across generational and ideological divides. Together, they established an avant-garde musical tradition that pushed against the limitations of strict chronological time and instrumentalized discourses of backwardness and forwardness to articulate a Polish road to modernity. This is a history that resists Cold War periodization, opening up new ways of thinking about nations and nationalism in the second half of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAvant-garde (Music)zPolandxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusiczPolandy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975422?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975422/original  a978-3-11-069041-5  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles